To determine life-cycle costs, the Department, in cooperation with the Maryland Energy Administration, shall establish standards that require at least:
an evaluation of:
the amount and type of glass used in the building and the directions of exposure;
the effect of insulation incorporated into the design of the building;
the effect of the use of active and passive solar energy systems;
if wind or solar energy is used, the orientation and integration of the building with respect to its site; and
the variable occupancy and operating conditions of the building and its parts;
an energy consumption analysis of each major piece of equipment in any of the following systems serving the building:
the cooling system;
the heating system;
the hot water system;
the lighting system;
the ventilation system; and
any other major energy-using system; and
a comparison of possible alternative energy systems:
that would use the most plentiful and available energy resources in combinations that would result in maximum energy efficiency, both in the building and at the source; and
with respect to the projected annual energy consumption of the major energy-using equipment of each system over the life of the building.
